<div xmlns:java="http://xml.apache.org/xslt/java" id="centre_col"><!-- begin original content --><h1>ESSUM35820 - Requirements relating
to share options - exercise rights: Ceasing to be in scheme related
employment</h1>
<br>
<p>Sub-paragraph 34 (5) permits schemes to provide rights of early
exercise when an option- holder ceases to be in scheme related
employment due to the transfer of a business.
<br>
<br> The only other rights of early exercise following cessation
of employment are in the compulsory provisions of paragraph 34 (2).
Paragraphs 34 (2), 34 (5) and 36 are the only circumstances in
which anyone not in eligible employment can participate (obtain or
exercise options) in a SAYE share option scheme (paragraph 10 (1)).
<br>
<br> Paragraph 34 (5) covers circumstances in which, although the
scheme related employment has ceased, the option-holder may still
be working in the same job:</p>
<br>
<ol type="1" start="1">
<li>Transfer of employing company out of the scheme

organiser&rsquo;s group - so that the company (although remaining

the employer) can no longer be a constituent company.

<br>
<br>
</li>
<li>Transfer of the business in which the employee works from a

constituent company to a person who is neither associated with the

scheme organiser nor a company of which the scheme organiser has

control - so that the employer changes and the employees are no

longer employed by the constituent company.

<br>
<br>
</li>
</ol>
<p>If the Scheme rules make provisions under paragraph 34 (5) to

permit exercise of options then the rules must specify which of the

following applies:</p>
<br>
<ul>
<li class="filledcircle">within six months of the termination date

(the date when scheme related employment ends) or</li>
<li class="filledcircle">that the options may be exercised within 6

months after the date (if any) when cessation occurs for a reason

within paragraph 34 (2) (a) or (b) (see 

<a href="ESSUM35610.htm">ESSUM35610</a>), which prior to the

termination date was the scheme related employment.</li>
</ul>
<p>The practical effect of this second alternative is that the

participant would retain his option even though he was no longer

employed in a company that has any connection with the scheme

organiser. The fact that the scheme organiser would still have

reporting obligations in relation to options held in these

circumstances may mean that scheme rules will normally specify the

first alternative. This alternative provision was brought in as

part of FA 2003 and took effect from 10 July 2003.

<br>
<br> Paragraph 36 permits schemes to provide rights of exercise

within 6 months of the bonus date when an option holder is not

employed by a constituent company if, at the bonus date, the option

holder holds an office or employment in a company which is</p>
<br>
<ul>
<li class="filledcircle">an associated company of the scheme

organiser, but</li>
<li class="filledcircle">not a constituent company</li>
</ul>
